Alzheimers Behaviorial Phenotypes

2024-07-02

First we need some R libraries:

#remotes::install_github("https://github.com/monarch-initiative/monarchr", ref = "engines")

suppressMessages({
    library(monarchr)
    library(ggraph)
    library(stringr) # for str_wrap
    library(tidygraph) # activate() etc.
})

Lets start by looking for Alzheimers. Well use the search here in R to see what we can see:

monarch_engine() |>
    search_nodes("Alzheimer")

There it is, MONDO:0004975. Lets get it and all the descendants, and make a quick plot. Well investigate the phenotypes connected to these below.

alz <- monarch_engine() |>
    fetch_nodes(query_ids = "MONDO:0004975") |> # Down
    expand(predicates = "biolink:subclass_of", direction = "in", transitive = TRUE)

quickplot <- function(g) {
    ggraph(g, layout = "sugiyama") +
        geom_edge_link(aes(color = predicate),
                                     arrow = arrow(length = unit(2, 'mm'), type = "closed"),
                                     end_cap = circle(2.5, 'mm')) +
        geom_node_point(aes(color = pcategory),
                                        size = 3) +
        geom_node_label(aes(label = str_wrap(name, 20)),
                                        size = 2,
                                        repel = TRUE,
                                        check_overlap = TRUE,
                                        fill = "#FFFFFF88") 
}

26 3 UPHENO:0080585 biolink:subclass_of UPHENO:0049622 not_provided not_provided monarch-kg_edges.jsonl c(infores:monarchinitiative, infores:phenio) infores:upheno phenio_edges urn:uuid:85abd002-0b9e-4f3b-84e9-1636351f34cd c(biolink:Association, biolink:Entity)

Over 700 subtypes of atypical behavior, and 26 ancestors; lets plot the latter to see if there are more general terms we should consider.

quickplot(atypical_behaviors_anc)

So there are a two higher-level entities that we might use instead of Atypical behavior - abnormal behavior and Abnormality of mental function. Lets get the subtypes of both of those.

atypical_behaviors <- atypical_behaviors_anc |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(name == "abnormal behavior") |>
    expand(predicates = "biolink:subclass_of", direction = "in", transitive = TRUE)

Next, the complete subtypes for Abnormality of mental function.

atypical_mental_functions <- atypical_behaviors_anc |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(name == "Abnormality of mental function") |>
    expand(predicates = "biolink:subclass_of", direction = "in", transitive = TRUE)

atypical_mental_functions

Lets filter the nodes in these graphs to see what they have in common and uniquely. Well also add type labels to the result for later use, with both meaning a phenotype that is a descendant of both Behavioral and Mental abnormalities.

# first: what's in atypical behaviors not in atypical mental functions
behavioral_only <- atypical_behaviors |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(!id %in% nodes(atypical_mental_functions)$id) |>
    mutate(type = "behavioral")

# what's in atypical mental functions not atypical behaviors
mental_only <- atypical_mental_functions |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(!id %in% nodes(atypical_behaviors)$id) |>
    mutate(type = "mental")

HP:0033849 biolink:PhenotypicFeature Bilingual aphasia The term bilingual aphasia is used to refer to aphasia in persons who speak two or more languages. When a multilingual speaker has aphasia following a stroke, the languages spoken premorbidly may show comparable or differential patterns of impairment. Differential patterns may manifest as greater impairment in one language compared to another, or as differences in the characteristics of aphasia. Clinical reports of bilingual aphasia show dissociations in the processing of the language learned first (L1) and and second (L2), with one language more impaired than the other. Other cases show a pattern of differential recovery where L2 is recovered only after L1. Another pattern is alternating antagonism; i.e., patients access one language in spontaneous speech and inhibit the other language for alternating periods. This term should be used for a type of aphasia in a person who speaks multiple languages in which the impairment is different for different languages. Ok, 24 behavioral only, 97 mental only, 724 both.

Lets join them back together (bringing in the labels we defined above). Well also grab the phenotypes associated with Alzheimers (along with the nodes for Alzheimers itself), then join the two together to bring in the label info. Well need to then cut this back down to just the nodes that are related to Alzheimers. Finally well create a plot of Alzheimers phenotypes labeled by their type.

# combine the three sets above into a single table
all_behavioral_mental_phenos <- behavioral_only |>
    graph_join(mental_only) |>
    graph_join(behavioral_and_mental)

# alzheimers diseases and phenos
alz_phenos <- alz %>%
    expand(result_categories = "biolink:PhenotypicFeature")

# all behavioral, mental, and alzheimers phenotypes, labeled
all_behavioral_mental_alz_phenos <- alz_phenos |>
    graph_join(all_behavioral_mental_phenos) |>
    mutate(type = ifelse(is.na(type), "other", type))

# finally, let's flush out the nodes that are not in the alz_phenos graph
alz_phenos_labeled <- all_behavioral_mental_alz_phenos |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(id %in% nodes(alz_phenos)$id)

alz_phenos_labeled

        geom_edge_link(aes(color = predicate),

#ggraph(behavioral_mental_alz_phenos, layout = "sugiyama") +

alz_phenos_labeled |>
    activate(nodes) |>
    filter(pcategory == "biolink:PhenotypicFeature") |>
    select(id, name, type, description) |>
    arrange(type)

In general, this can refer to neurological diseases but also fractures or other sources of pain that is triggered upon walking. However, in the current context gait disturbance refers to difficulty walking on the basis of a neurological or muscular disease. both

HP:0001332 Dystonia An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk. both
HP:0012433 Abnormal social behavior An abnormality of actions or reactions of a person taking place during interactions with others. both
HP:0000657 Oculomotor apraxia Ocular motor apraxia is a deficiency in voluntary, horizontal, lateral, fast eye movements (saccades) with retention of slow pursuit movements. The inability to follow objects visually is often compensated by head movements. There may be decreased smooth pursuit, and cancellation of the vestibulo-ocular reflex. both
HP:0001251 Ataxia Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. This causes a variety of elementary neurological deficits including asynergy (lack of coordination between muscles, limbs and joints), dysmetria (lack of ability to judge distances that can lead to under- or overshoot in grasping movements), and dysdiadochokinesia (inability to perform rapid movements requiring antagonizing muscle groups to be switched on and off repeatedly). both

HP:0000006 Autosomal dominant inheritance A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in heterozygotes. In the context of medical genetics, an autosomal dominant disorder is caused when a single copy of the mutant allele is present. Males and females are affected equally, and can both transmit the disorder with a risk of 50% for each child of inheriting the mutant allele. other
